products.title: Pen-Go Titanium Pen
products.body_html:
Weighing just 1/2oz (14g) and measuring only 2.88" (73mm), the Pen-Go in titanium is one stealthy little writing instrument. Machined from solid aerospace grade-5 titanium, the Pen-Go is the perfect compliment for your favorite titanium tool watch, knife, or as a stand alone implement for easy carrying in a suit pocket or to lighten your load while hitting the great outdoors.

The ink cartridge is a medium-tipped black unit that will function from -30F (-34C) to +250F (121C). The pen was supplied to fill a large military contract, so commercial quantities are limited. We are excited to be able to offer the Pen-Go Titanium here at The Hodinkee Shop.

- Made from grade-5 titanium
- 0.5oz / 14g
- 2.88" / 73mm
- Refill: Lamy M22 Black Medium

products.title: Brass Pen Dock
products.body_html:
This solid brass pen dock is a handsome and useful desk accessory that will show a natural patina over time. We admire the high quality brass and precision machining, which are immediately evident in hand. Unmistakably a nod to standard dice, when loaded up this turns out to be a surprisingly ideal pen holding arrangement.

Perfect for storing pens, the brass pen dock is also perfect for everything from fine fountain pens to your average ballpoint affair and, of course, the ubiquitous Sharpie. At 11oz (312g), this pend dock is pleasingly substantial in hand and more than secure when loaded up with your writing instruments.

- Limited edition of 200.
- Solid brass that will age over time
- 1.75" x 1.75" x 1.5"
- 312g / 11oz
- C360 machining for ultra smooth finish
- Includes laser-cut felt pad for the bottom

products.title: Copper Dice Set
products.body_html:
If you take your gaming seriously and enjoy fine craftsmanship as you play, this set of copper dice are the ideal upgrade. Precision cut from solid copper, these dice will develop a natural patina over time. Whether a family heirloom to hand down for generations, the perfect gift, or perhaps both, these dice will grow more unique and memorable with time.

At 15mm and weighing one ounce each, these are substantial dice that will transform rolling into a satisfying tactile experience. When not in use, these copper dice make a handsome decor accent or even a paper weight for your desk.

products.title: 1960s Girard-Perregaux Gyromatic Ref. 6373
products.body_html:
Why This Watch Matters

Let's get Gyromatic.

The Full Story

Girard-Perregaux was founded in 1791, and among the countless designs it has released over more than two centuries, some of its most famous creations include the three-bridge tourbillon and the Laureato sport watch series. When the Gryomatic was released in 1957,  it was intended to be Girard-Perregaux's answer for a reliable automatic movement. Girard-Perregaux developed a system by which a self-winding module could be added to an existing manual movement. The system utilized a unidirectional winding system that relied on two "Gyrotron" wheels with rubies, instead of ball bearings, intended to prevent wear and friction.

We have been lucky enough to offer a few really interesting Gyromatic examples in the past, however, this one has to be the best (sorry other Gyros, you're all loved). With salmon-esque dial tone and thick bezel, the look is precisely vintage feeling. While the price point may suggest Gyromatics were bargain bin scores, handling these watches in the metal is a whole different experience. Every detail is consistently well-thought-out and well-executed – to an impressive level really.



The Fine Print

Maker: Girard-Perregaux
Model: Gyromatic
Reference: 6373
Year: 1960s
Case No: N/A
Material: Stainless steel
Dimensions: 33.5mm diameter; 10.5mm thickness
Crystal: Plexiglass
Lume: None
Caliber: Girard-Perregaux, self-winding, caliber 47A (ETA 1256)
Bracelet/Strap: HODINKEE The Barrett Calfskin Watch Strap In Tan
Lug Width: 18mm
Box/Papers: No

What We Love And What You Should Know

Things We Love:

- Salmon / light gold dial patina
- Interesting case shape with large bezel
- Applied dial details

Things To Know:

- Scratches on case
- Scratch on bezel at 6 o'clock
- Wear on crown

This Girard-Perregaux is in good, honest condition. The case has a few light scratches and handling marks. The bezel has a few light marks such as at 6 o'clock. The caseback has a few scratches from opening but remains in good condition. The crown appears to be gold plated to match the dial details and shows some regular wear while presenting nicely.

The dial is in good condition with patina throughout that presents as a light gold or salmon tone. The hour markers have developed a light patina. The hands show some oxidation that is in line with the age of the watch.

The inside caseback is signed by Girard-Perregaux as well as the movement and dial. This watch was photographed on a 175mm/6.9inch wrist.

The Full Story

The Vulcain Cricket was introduced in 1947 at an event at the Waldorf Astoria in New York City. It was one of the first wristwatches with a mechanical alarm built in. It has a long history, highlighted by the fact that a Cricket has been gifted to every president from Truman to Biden (excluding George W. Bush), earning it the title of the "Watch of Presidents." You can read more about the history of the Vulcain Cricket here.

Setting the alarm function is straightforward and easy. The watch must first be wound (forward and backward, for timekeeping and alarm functions). Next, press the pusher down at two o'clock until it clicks. This will eject the crown, which can then be rotated to set the alarm. The fourth hand acts as its indicator. Simply push the crown in, and the alarm is set and ready to go.

The present example features a silvered dial with applied hour markers and dauphine hands in a gold tone. Despite the 34mm diameter, the Vulcain Cricket is well-known for having a substantial wrist presence with nicely elongated and curved lugs. We think it will wear suitably on most wrist sizes.

products.title: 1979 Rolex Sea-Dweller Ref. 1665 'Great White'
products.body_html:
Why This Watch Matters

An all-time great if-you-know-you-know Rolex, the "Great White."

The Full Story

The Sea-Dweller ref. 1665 first debuted circa 1967 and was designed for use during saturation diving. The main differences between the 'Red' Submariner and Double Red Sea-Dweller are the thicker case, the helium escape valve (HEV), the Sea-Dweller moniker on the dial, and the domed crystal without the Cyclops date lens. The origin of the nickname "Great White" comes from the lack of red text on the dial, rather all of the text is white.

The present example is from 1979 and features a "Mark I" dial. This was the second white dial variation after Rolex made the switch away from the "Double Red" to the "Great White." The watch is in great, honest condition. Sea-Dwellers were typically used for diving, so not many survived in good, original condition. This watch has aged quite beautifully over the years, and all the lume has turned to a slightly off-white color. Overall, this is a great example of an iconic dive watch.

On the wrist, the Great White just works so well. The proportions offer a substantial feeling while not taking over your entire wrist. The patina here is really pleasing, and I know we say that often, but here it's extraordinarily well-aged and gorgeous. The domed crystal just begs the wearer to be mesmerized, rolling the watch to view it from different angles and understand how that expertly contoured Sea-Dweller crystal shows off the dial.

products.title: 1980s Patek Philippe Golden Ellipse Ref. 3788 With 'Sigma' Dial
products.body_html:
Why This Watch Matters

A Golden Ellipse adhering to the golden ratio with a gold case and dial.

The Full Story

The minimalist aesthetics of the Golden Ellipse's oval-shaped case with simple baton hour markers and hands have been in the company's collection since 1968. The design is said to be based on the golden ratio derived by ancient Greek mathematicians. No wonder we're immediately drawn to it.

Collectability's John Reardon – formerly of Christie's, Sotheby's, and Patek Philippe USA –  described the Ellipse as, "the canvas to tell the story of Patek Philippe to the world," at the time of its development and introduction in 1968. In the face of the looming quartz crisis, Patek made a conscious effort through the 1960s to acquire Switzerland's best craftsmen, whom the brand had traditionally hired on a third-party basis, bringing world-class bracelet, dial, and case manufacturing under one roof and under the Calatrava cross. The brand saw its Ellipse collection, designed and developed by these now in-house makers, as a work of art more than a timepiece. Advertisements of the era marketed the Ellipse as a "non-watch," explaining that "people who merely need to know the time of day will choose a watch, not a Patek Philippe." For more information about what the Ellipse collection means to the brand and collectors today, check out Mr. Reardon's video here.

Today's example is a Golden Ellipse with a quartz movement that was first introduced in 1982 and produced for approximately a decade. The ref. 3788 features a dial and bezel in the classic 1.6 to 1 "golden ratio" that the entire collection was built off of as well as hidden lugs. These integrate the strap in a way that highlights the real star of the show, the proportion and finishing of the case and dial. Finally, an iconic design cue of the Ellipse collection is the blued gold dial, like the one we have here. 

Additionally, the dial is made entirely of gold, as indicated by the "Sigma'' symbols at the bottom of the dial. The Sigma indication was part of a larger effort by the Swiss watch industry trade association l’Association pour la Promotion Industrielle de l'Or (APRIOR) to emphasize the value of watches using any gold material. The finish is actually a bit of a secret for Patek; some proprietary process within the manufacturer's walls turns an 18k gold dial blue for a result that's uniquely stunning in the metal.

products.title: 1930s Omega 'Trident'
products.body_html:
Why This Watch Matters

The first of its kind to hit the HODINKEE Shop, this Omega "Trident" packs plenty of punch in a smaller footprint.

The Full Story

We continue to search for these simple, time-only Omega watches to include in our vintage drops here at HODINKEE. The brand frankly made a lot of watches, and its less complicated offerings remain relatively accessible while still touting the high level of finishing and quality that the watch world has come to expect from Omega.

Patina or no patina? That's the ultimate question when it comes to vintage watches. And when you come across one like this Omega, you simply can't ignore the beauty in imperfection and wabi-sabi that separates vintage watches from their contemporary peers.

We believe this Omega to fall under the Medicus model line of the late 1930s which was the brand's first watch to feature a center sweep seconds hand. That simple feature found its way into various iterations but few stand out quite as much as the so-called "trident." Named, of course, for the trident-shaped hour hand, we really don't come across these all too often making this one truly special to offer. The 29mm stainless steel case features, apt to the nickname, a screwdown caseback for some 1930s-era water resistance and really wears well today as an under-the-radar vintage gem.
